    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, i'm studying for my checkride and i'm a bit confused about pitot tubes. can u explain how they actually work to measure airspeed? specifically how the pressure difference creates the reading?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, I can help with that! Pitot tubes measure airspeed by comparing the static air pressure with the dynamic air pressure. When an aircraft moves through the air, the pitot tube captures the dynamic pressure from the airflow, which is the pressure when the air is moving. This dynamic pressure is compared to the static pressure, which is the atmospheric pressure where the aircraft is flying. The difference between these pressures is converted into an airspeed reading, which helps pilots understand how fast they're going relative to the air around them. Think of it like the pressure difference is like the speed of the wind in relation to the stationary air. The faster the wind moves, the greater the difference in pressure. That's how pilots get their airspeed readings. Hope that clears things up!",
      "source": "target",
